This isn't a bad idea and indeed it has been suggested before.

Indeed, I tried it and got flamed by the purists [nee unrealists]
who think that BITNET should use domain names.  Some sites do,
and some sites don't.  As for the idea itself, it needs a little
refinement.  First, you don't want all bitnet mail traveling to
blanket gateways.  You want it going to the nearest gateway.  As
an Internet/BITNET mail maintainer, I would feel better having
it traverse the Internet before going into the hole (I have seen
mailers [and listserv] do some really twisted header munging on
BITNET).

So, a better choice would be to have the INTER/BIT gateways show
low MX values (like 10) for specific sites nearby (ie: CS.McGill.CA
might advertise MX 10's for MUSOCS, CONU1, MCGILL1, LAVALVM1, etc
-- all within 3 hops) and a high value (say MX 30) record for
*.BITNET.  The only case this looses is when the gateway is very
close by.  But then one can always cheat and lie to the nameserver,
ie. "*.BITNET MX 10 local-gateway".

I will probably be crucified for suggesting such hacks, but then
some of us like a solution that works (instead of looking good).

I'll just wait for someone to explain to me that I don't understand
how the DNS works...

-Philip

